'''Adam de Lathbury, O.S.B.''', otherwise known as '''Adam of [[Lathbury]]''' or '''Adam [[Lothbury]]''', was a [[Order of St. Benedict|Benedictine]] [[monk]] who ruled as [[Abbot]] of [[Reading Abbey]], in the [[England|English]] county of [[Berkshire]], from 1226 to 1238.<ref name=rbhabrdg>{{cite web |url=http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/abbots_reading.html |title=Abbots of Reading, Berkshire |author=Ford, David Nash |year=2001 |work=Royal Berkshire History |publisher=Nash Ford Publishing |accessdate=28 December 2010}}</ref>

In 1233, a group of [[friar]]s of the [[Franciscan]] Order arrived in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] with the intention of creating a community to minister to the poor and the oppressed. This arrival was not welcomed by the established Reading Abbey, but the fact that the friars had [[patronage|royal patronage]] meant that Abbot Adam was obliged to assist. He granted them a site alongside the road to [[Caversham Bridge]], but the site proved prone to flooding, and they later moved to the site now occupied by the town's [[Greyfriars Church, Reading|Greyfriars Church]].<ref name=dptsor32>{{cite book | first = Daphne | last = Phillips | title = The Story of Reading | year = 1980 | publisher = Countryside Books | isbn = 0-905392-07-8 | pages = 32}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=40066 | title = Victoria County History: A History of the County of Berkshire, Volume 2 (Friaries: The grey friars of Reading) | pages = 89–91 | accessdate = 2016-07-22}}</ref>

